What I say to my non-American friends
CAMBRIDGE – I often travel abroad and my foreign friends ask me every time, with varying degrees of perplexity: but what exactly is happening in your country ?
Here's the translated sentence.
Firstly, be careful not to misinterpret the 2016 elections.
In contrast to some comments, the American political system has not been swept away by a wave of populism.
It is true that we have a long history of rebellion against the elite.
Donald Trump exploited the vein of a tradition associated with leaders like Andrew Jackson and William Jennings Bryan in the 19th century and Huey Long and George Wallace in the 20th century.
Yet Trump fell short of winning the popular vote by nearly three million votes.
He won the election by appealing to populist resentment in three Rust Belt states (Michigan, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin), which had previously voted for the Democratic Party.
If a hundred thousand votes had been cast differently in those states, Trump would have lost the electoral college and the presidency.
This, however, raises the real issue of growing social and regional inequalities in the United States.
J.D. Vance's latest bestseller, Hillbilly Elegy, convincingly describes the vast difference between California and Appalachia.
Research by Princeton economists Anne Case and Angus Deaton shows that demographic trends among low-income white Americans without college degrees are worse than those of African Americans, who historically have been at the bottom of the inequality spectrum.
In 1999, mortality rates among whites without higher education were 30% below those of African Americans; by 2015, they were 30% higher.
In addition, employment in the manufacturing industry, which was once one of the main sources of high-paying jobs for working-class whites, has sharply declined over the past generation, making up only 2% of the workforce.
These former Democratic voters were swayed by Trump's promises to shake things up and bring back manufacturing jobs.
Paradoxically, Trump's efforts to repeal President Barack Obama's healthcare legislation may end up making their lives even harder.
One shouldn't underestimate Trump's communication skills.
Many people are shocked by his Twitter rants and his outrageous disdain for the facts.
But Trump is a veteran of reality TV, where he learned that the key to success is to monopolize viewers' attention by formulating extreme statements, regardless of the truth.
Twitter allows him to set the agenda and distract his critics.
What irritates commentators in the media and academic circles doesn't bother his supporters.
But as soon as he transitions from his self-focused campaign to attempts at governing, Twitter becomes a double-edged sword that discourages some crucial allies he desperately needs.
Thirdly, I tell my friends not to expect normal behavior.
Normally, a president who loses the popular vote typically moves towards the center of the political spectrum in order to garner more support.
It's what George W. Bush successfully did in 2001.
Trump, on the other hand, claims to have won the popular vote and, by acting as if this were true, wins over his core supporters.
Although Trump made solid centrist nominations at the Department of Defense, the Department of State, and the National Security Agency, his choices for the Environmental Protection Agency and the Department of Health and Human Services place him at the extremes of the Republican Party.
His White House staff is divided between ideologues and pragmatists - and he aims to please both camps simultaneously.
Fourthly, the American institutions should not be underestimated.
Sometimes my friends talk as if the sky is falling on their heads and ask me if Trump is as dangerous a narcissist as Mussolini.
I tell them not to panic.
The United States, despite many problems, are not the Italy of 1922.
Our national political elites are often polarized; but America's founders were just as polarized.
In the drafting of the United States' Constitution, the founders' objective was not to ensure that the government be harmonious, but to limit political power to a system of checks and balances that would make it difficult to exercise such power.
A joke on the subject says that the founders created a political system such that it would be impossible for King George to rule over us - impossible for him or anyone else.
Inefficiency has been harnessed for the sake of freedom.
Trump's presidency is still in its infancy, and we can't be sure what might happen after, say, a major terrorist attack.
So far, however, the courts, Congress, and the states have watched over this balance of powers within the administration, as Madison had wished.
And career officials in executive branch agencies still carry significant weight.
Finally, my friends wonder what all this means for American foreign policy and the liberal international order led by the United States since 1945.
Honestly, I don't know, but I worry less about China's rise than Trump's.
Although American leaders, including Obama, have complained about freeloaders, the United States has long taken the lead in providing important global public goods: security, a stable international reserve currency, relatively open markets, and management of the world's common resources.
Despite the problems of the international order under US leadership, the world has prospered and poverty has been reduced under this order.
No one can claim with certainty that this will continue.
The United States will have to cooperate with China, Europe, Japan, and other countries to manage transnational issues.
During the 2016 campaign, Trump was the first major party candidate in 70 years to challenge the American alliance system.
Since his inauguration in January, Trump's and his team's statements suggest that he may persist in this direction.
The power to coerce and the power to persuade of the United States, after all, comes in large part from the fact that the United States has 60 allies (while China has only a few).
But the stability of multilateral institutions, which help manage the global economy and the planet's common resources, is more uncertain.
The Director of the Budget of the Department of State under Trump speaks of a budget of coercive power, with budget cuts made to the Department of State and the United Nations system.
Other members of the government advocate for replacing multilateral trade agreements with "fair and balanced" bilateral arrangements. Trump rejects Obama's efforts to address climate change.
I wish I could reassure my friends about these issues.
I am not able.
